\begin_layout Subsection
Bushfire and heatwave weather patterns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The replication of the analysis comparing bushfire and heatwave weather
 patterns confirms the results found in Chapter 4.
 The results are robust for daily as well as seasonal time scales.
 The linkages with ENSO patterns also remain valid.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The daily composites show the most consistent results.
 For air temperature, using alternative bushfire and heatwave data reveals
 that the differences in their weather patterns remain.
 Cold fronts remain the most important fire weather feature.
 On the other hand, persistent heat anomalies characterize heatwaves events.
 Relative humidity patterns confirm that heatwaves in Victoria present dry
 anomalies in this region with wet anomlies in several other areas of the
 continent.
 During bushfires in Victoria, Australia is predominantly dry.
 The composites produced using alternative data are also capable of reproducing
 the contrasting intensity of the wave patterns during bushfires and heatwaves.
 These anomalies also confirm the intense wave train pattern linked to frontal
 activity during fire events.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a daily time scale, the results show that the intensity of the frontal
 activity is the most important feature of extreme fire weather in Victoria.
 Therefore, indices aiming to predict fire weather with days in advance
 could focus on metrics to evaluate the strength of cold fronts.
 This contradicts the current state of practise where the FFDI, an index
 whose most sensitive paramater is temperature, is the most commonly used
 tool for fire emergencies.
 Consequently, fire weather danger estimated by the FFDI might be misleading
 during heatwave events.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Alternative indices based on the effect of frontal activity over extreme
 fire weather have already been published in the literature.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mills2005"

\end_inset

 proposed a simple alternative based on this criteria.
 The author argues that measuring the 850 hPa horizontal temperature gradient
 is a useful metric to anticipate extreme fire weather.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Reeder2015"

\end_inset

 proposed a similar parameter.
 They used the difference in surface temperature after cold front passages
 (∆ 17 
\begin_inset script superscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
o
\end_layout

\end_inset

C) to identify extreme fire weather days.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mills2005"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Reeder2015"

\end_inset

 criteria have been used to study past extreme fire weather and make projections
 (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hasson2009"

\end_inset

).
 Since there are already alternative fire weather metrics on a daily time
 scale this research focused on the development of a new index for seasonal
 prediction.
 Therefore, the seasonal patterns are also discussed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a seasonal time scale, bushfire and heatwave weather patterns also display
