\begin_layout Subsection
Fire weather metrics, drivers and predictability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, ERA-20C data reveal more consistency with observations than its
 20CR counterpart (check).
 Therefore, this part of the discussion re-examines several aspects already
 discussed in Chapter 5.
 For example, the performance of the VSBI in comparison to seasonal metrics
 of the FFDI.
 Additionally, it also debates the influence of local climate variables
 and remote drivers of fire weather.
 Finally, it discusses the potential to predict seasonal fire weather and
 activity in Victoria.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The VSBI is an equivalent metric of fire weather in comparison to seasonal
 metrics of the FFDI.
 The results show that they are highly correlated during spring and summer.
 They also show that their relationship with fire activity in summer is
 similar.
 The simplification of the relationships between variables in the VSBI equation
 does not demonstrate to significantly affect the results in comparison
 to the FFDI.
 Additionally, the VSBI has the advantage to be simpler to compute than
 the FFDI.
 However, the VSBI equation might overestimate ENSO's influence over fire
 weather.
 In fact, the correlations show that its influence is considerably lower
 in comparison to local climate variables.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regional climate conditions drive fire weather in Victoria.
 The results demonstrate that remote drivers have less influence than climate
 variables.
 These findings agree with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Harris2013"

\end_inset

.
 However, climate modes of variability do play a role in driving fire weather.
 For example, ENSO and IOD moderately influence relative humidity.
 This variable showed to be the principal component of fire weather metrics.
 Additionally, it also demonstrated to have a moderate influence on fire
 activity.
 However, ENSO and IOD's influence is not constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remote fire weather drivers evolve from spring to summer.
 During spring, the IOD and ENSO show a similar level of influence.
 Furthermore, these two climate modes are highly correlated.
 This result is consistent with the correlations presented in Chapter 5.
 This finding contrast with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Cai2009"

\end_inset

.
 This thesis found no evidence to show that the IOD has a significantly
 higher influence than ENSO during this season.
 On the other hand, during summer, the IOD does not exert influence over
 fire weather.
 This behaviour was expected from the seasonal dynamic of this driver.
 Unexpectedly, the influence of ENSO weakens during this season.
 Previous studies (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Williams1999"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Harris2013"

\end_inset

) used an extended fire season (November-March) which did not allow analyse
 the evolution of the influence of this driver.
 This finding suggests that the effect of remote climate drivers is greater
 in spring than summer.
 The weather patterns consistently support this thesis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The VSBI computed using observational data shows a high forecasting skill.
 These data also demonstrate that the VSBI has greater predictive power
 than climate variables and indices.
 Additionally, results using observations show coherent relationships between
 the prediction of fire weather and activity.
 For example, greater skill to predict fire weather than activity.
 On the other hand, using reanalysis data, there is consistency to show
 that the VSBI has greater forecasting skill than climate indices.
 However, some inconsistencies persist using ERA-20C.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The VSBI does not show entirely consistent results using reanalysis data.
 In spite that the ERA-20C data demonstrates a greater level of agreement
 with observations than 20CR; these data shows that the index has a comparable
 forecasting skill than climate variables.
 Additionally, both reanalysis datasets show the greater predictive ability
 for fire events rather than fire weather (check).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These inconsistencies show the limitations of these reanalysis datasets
 to conduct regional climate studies.
 Their resolution could be a caveat for this analysis.
 In contrast, both datasets showed substantial agreement when they were
 used to investigate large-scale weather patterns.
 On the other hand, data from more weather stations may be necessary to
 have more robust agreements—currently not available—.
\end_layout

